	Software Downloads	

 ZPlot® and ZView®



ZPlot® performs Electrochemical Impedance Spectroscopy measurements.  ZPlot is compatible with Frequency Response Analyzers from Solartron Analytical and potentiostats from Scribner Associates, Solartron Analytical, EG&G Princeton Applied Research (PAR), and AMEL. License Required.
ZView® is the world's leading software for graphing and analysis of impedance data. License required. A list of compatible data file types can be found here.
 

ZPlot® and ZView® Software Updates/Upgrades Version 3.5c (4/13/17) is now available. ZPlot 3.x combines all of the functions of the old ZPlot 2.x, 1.x and Z60 1.x while adding many new features. This version is fully compatible with Win7/Win8/Win10.
Download ZPlot Version 3.5c
Release Notes
Download ZView Version 3.5c
Release Notes
 
To keep our records accurate, please complete the Product Registration Form.

Download and Installation Instructions
All programs in this web site contain a full setup program and all necessary program files compressed into a single executable program. When the downloaded file is run, it will install the program.
You may wish to print this page for future reference.

Download a file by clicking on the file name. Your web browser may say that it does not know how to handle the file and give you several choices - select 'Save to File'. Note the directory where it is saved.
After the file has been downloaded, run the file by double-clicking on it in Windows Explorer
Whenever possible, use the default directory names suggested by the installer.




















Scribner Associates Inc. 


Is a leading developer of high-quality instrumentation and software for the electrochemical research and development (R&D) community. Scribner Associates’ hardware and software products are used by academic, private and government laboratories in the areas of fuel cell development and evaluation, battery and redox flow cell technology, corrosion science and engineering, electrochemical sensors and multi-electrode arrays.
Read more








